# Plan implementation protocol

When the user asks you to implement a plan (a markdown document from `plans/`), you are the **implementing agent**. The plan was created using the `planning` skill (`.cursor/skills/planning/`) and is your spec. Follow this protocol exactly.

## Detect plan type

First, determine what you've been given:

- **Phase implementation doc** (`<name>-phase-N-IMPL.md`): a self-contained spec for one phase of a larger plan. This is the most common handoff for complex work. Implement only this phase.
- **Simple plan** (`<name>-PLAN.md` with inline deliverables, no phase docs): a single-file plan. Implement the full plan.
- **Master plan** (`<name>-PLAN.md` that references phase docs): do NOT implement directly. Tell the user: *"This is a master plan with separate phase docs. Which phase should I implement? I see: [list phase docs]."*

If the user says "implement the whole plan" for a master plan with phase docs, implement **one phase at a time in separate passes**. Start with Phase 1, complete the self-audit, and stop. The user will hand you the next phase doc in a new conversation.

## Phase 0 — Extract the contract (MANDATORY, do this FIRST)

1. Read the plan or phase document **in full** before writing any code.
2. Locate the **Deliverables Manifest** section. If the plan lacks one, stop and tell the user: *"This plan has no deliverables manifest. I need a numbered list of every file to create, modify, or delete before I can begin. Should I extract one from the plan for your approval, or do you want to add it?"*
3. For phase docs: check the **Prerequisites** section. Verify that prior phase outputs exist (check for the files/APIs listed). If prerequisites are not met, stop and tell the user: *"Phase N requires [X] from Phase N-1, but I can't find it. Has Phase N-1 been implemented?"*
4. Copy the manifest into a TODO list (use the todo tool). Each deliverable becomes one todo item with its exact file path, operation (NEW/MOD/DELETE), and one-line description.
5. Read the TODO list back to the user and ask: *"This is my implementation checklist extracted from the plan. Should I proceed, or do you want to adjust anything?"*
6. **Do not write any code until the user confirms.**

## Phase 1 — Implement deliverables

Check whether the plan/phase doc defines **Parallel tracks**. This determines the execution strategy.

### Sequential execution (no parallel tracks)

Work through the TODO list **sequentially by item number**. For each deliverable:

1. Re-read the relevant section from the plan/phase document. Do not rely on your memory of it — re-read it from the file.
2. Implement exactly what the plan specifies. Match file paths, module names, function signatures, and artifact types (rule vs skill, router vs service, etc.) to what the plan says.
3. After completing each deliverable, mark it complete in your TODO list.
4. For simple plans with multiple phases: at the end of each phase, pause and report to the user:
   - What was completed in this phase
   - Any deviations or issues encountered
   - Ask: *"Phase N complete. Should I continue to Phase N+1?"*

### Parallel execution (phase has parallel tracks)

When the plan defines parallel tracks with interface contracts, use sub-agents to implement tracks simultaneously.

**Step 1: Establish interface contracts.** Before launching any sub-agents, implement or codify any interface contracts defined in the plan. These are the boundaries parallel tracks build against. Depending on the plan, this may mean:
- Writing TypeScript type definitions or Python models for shared API shapes
- Creating stub files or placeholder endpoints that return the agreed contract shape
- Writing schema definitions that both tracks will use
- Or simply confirming the contracts are clearly stated in the plan (no code needed — the sub-agents read the plan)

**Step 2: Build sub-agent prompts.** For each track, construct a prompt that includes:
- The track's deliverables from the manifest (exact file paths and descriptions)
- The relevant technical detail section from the plan (copy the text — don't reference the file, since sub-agents may not have the same context)
- The interface contracts this track depends on (exact shapes, paths, status codes)
- The hard rules from this protocol (never substitute, never skip, never add unplanned files, ask if ambiguous)
- Instruction to report back: what was created, any deviations, any issues

**Step 3: Launch sub-agents in parallel.** Use the Task tool to launch one sub-agent per track. Choose the sub-agent type recommended in the plan (`generalPurpose` for code, `shell` for scripts, `browser-use` for UI work). Launch all independent tracks in a **single message** so they execute concurrently.

**Step 4: Collect results.** When sub-agents complete, review each result:
- Verify the reported deliverables match the plan
- Check for deviations or issues flagged by the sub-agent
- Mark completed items in the TODO list

**Step 5: Integration verification at sync points.** After all tracks in a parallel batch complete:
- Verify that parallel tracks produced compatible code (e.g., frontend calls match the API contract the backend implemented)
- Run any integration checks specified in the plan
- Fix integration issues before proceeding to the next batch or phase
- Report to the user: *"Parallel tracks A, B, C complete. Integration verified. [Any issues]. Should I continue?"*

**When NOT to parallelize**, even if the plan defines tracks:
- If the user explicitly asks for sequential execution
- If interface contracts are ambiguous or missing (ask the user to clarify first)
- If tracks have implicit dependencies the plan didn't capture (flag to the user)

## Hard rules — never violate these

- **Never substitute a different artifact type** than what the plan specifies. If the plan says "create a Cursor skill at `.cursor/skills/foo/SKILL.md`", do not create a Cursor rule at `.cursor/rules/foo.mdc` instead. If you believe the plan's choice is wrong, say so and ask — do not silently substitute.
- **Never skip a deliverable.** If a deliverable seems unnecessary or redundant, say so and ask — do not silently omit it.
- **Never add unplanned deliverables** of consequence (new services, new components, new config files) without telling the user. Minor implementation details (helper functions within a planned file, imports) are fine.
- **If anything is ambiguous, stop and ask.** Do not guess, do not improvise, do not default to a familiar pattern. The plan is the spec. If the spec is unclear, escalate to the user.

## Phase 2 — Self-audit (MANDATORY, do this LAST)

After all deliverables are complete:

1. Re-read the **Deliverables Manifest** from the plan/phase document (not from memory).
2. For each manifest item, verify the file exists at the specified path and the content matches the plan's intent.
3. Check for manifest items you missed.
4. Check for files you created that are NOT in the manifest — flag these to the user.
5. For phase docs: verify the **Acceptance Criteria** — check each criterion and report pass/fail.
6. For phase docs: verify the **Interface Contract** — confirm that the outputs later phases depend on are in place.
7. Report a final summary:

```
## Implementation audit
- Plan/phase: <filename>
- Execution mode: sequential / parallel (N tracks)
- Deliverables completed: X/Y
- Acceptance criteria: X/Y passed [list any failures]
- Deviations from plan: [list, or "None"]
- Unplanned files created: [list, or "None"]
- Items skipped: [list with reason, or "None"]
- Interface contract satisfied: [Yes/No, with details]
- Integration verification: [passed / failed, with details] (parallel only)
- Open issues: [list, or "None"]
- Ready for next phase: [Yes/No]
```

## Context management

Long plans strain context windows. To counteract this:

- **Phase docs are preferred** for complex work. They are self-contained and small enough to hold in full context.
- **Re-read plan sections** before implementing each deliverable — do not rely on what you remember from the initial read.
- **Use the TODO list** as your anchor. If you lose track of where you are, read the TODO list, not the full plan.
- If implementing a simple plan that exceeds ~400 lines, process it one phase at a time: read the phase, implement it, then move to the next phase with a fresh read.
